P1 orbital-transmitter capture-footprint external-validation reference
======================================================================

These fixtures externally validate Kshana's P1 orbital-transmitter capture
footprint (`antenna::pattern_gain_dbi`, `antenna::boresight_gain_dbi`,
`antenna::capture_footprint`) — see `tests/validate_p1_orbital_footprint.rs`.
They are not part of the Kshana source and are not shipped in the published
crates/packages; they exist only for the test suite.

Oracles
-------
1. scipy.special.j1 (SciPy 1.13.1) — an independent Bessel-J1 implementation
   (Cephes). Kshana's `antenna::bessel_j1` is instead the Abramowitz & Stegun
   9.4.4 / 9.4.6 *rational approximation*. Matching the resulting uniform
   circular-aperture pattern G(theta) = G0 + 10 log10([2 J1(x)/x]^2), with
   x = (pi D / lambda) sin theta, dB-for-dB is therefore a genuine cross-check of
   the pattern against a different J1 code path, not a self-comparison.

2. An independent numpy reconstruction of the footprint radiometry/geometry.
   Every formula (free-space path loss 20log10 d + 20log10 f + 20log10(4 pi / c);
   nadir-pointing-Tx slant range and off-nadir angle over a sphere of radius R;
   J/S = P_tx + gain - FSPL - AFS with both receiver gains zero and the AFS level
   as the authentic-signal power) is re-derived from first principles in Python.
   The only inputs shared with the Rust module are the physical constants
   (R_MOON, c, P_tx, D, f, eta, AFS, threshold) and the *definition* of the
   scenario — not any Kshana code. This is the same standard by which the DOP
   engine is validated against gnss_lib_py and the reference frames against ERFA.

Physics note (why there is no single "capture edge" angle)
----------------------------------------------------------
The aperture pattern has deep nulls and sidelobes, so J/S(gamma) is strongly
NON-monotone in the central angle gamma: the captured region is the main lobe
PLUS a handful of near-in sidelobe rings that still clear the 3 dB threshold, not
a single contiguous cap bounded by one threshold-crossing angle. The reference
therefore reconstructs the ENTIRE sweep point-by-point on Kshana's exact grid
(gamma_i = gamma_max * i/(n-1)) rather than a single crossing angle, which would
misrepresent the geometry. The area-weighted captured fraction is emitted using
Kshana's own DISCRETE weighting — sum(sin gamma_i | captured) / sum(sin gamma_i)
over the same grid — so it is the identical defined quantity, computed by an
independent implementation.

Files
-----
pattern_reference.csv   : theta_rad ; pattern_gain_dbi  (scipy-J1 pattern, 0..gamma_max)
sweep_reference.csv     : i ; central_angle_rad ; off_boresight_rad ; slant_m ;
                          gain_dbi ; js_db ; captured(0/1)  (per-point, n=400 grid)
geometry_reference.csv  : key ; value  (boresight_gain_dbi, horizon_central_angle_rad,
                          captured_fraction, nadir_js_db, limb_js_db, num_captured_points)

Provenance / reproducibility
----------------------------
Generated by the committed `generate_footprint_reference.py`, run offline with
numpy 2.0.2 + scipy 1.13.1 under Python 3 (no Kshana code involved):

    python3 generate_footprint_reference.py

Representative scenario (matches the P1 numeric target): D = 1 m, f = 2.4 GHz,
eta = 0.60, h = 100 km, P_tx = 40 W (16.0206 dBW), AFS = -140.6 dBW, 3 dB
capture threshold, n = 400 sweep points. Key results: boresight gain
25.792321 dBi; horizon central angle 0.331438376 rad; nadir J/S 42.361 dB;
limb J/S -11.784 dB (limb NOT captured); discrete captured fraction 0.030203
(65 of 400 grid points captured) — a small nadir-region set of rings, far from
the "whole visible hemisphere" the naive uniform-beam reading assumed.
